{"cursor":"55467","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Positivism' is a philosophy of science based on the view that information\nderived from sensory experience, logical and mathematical treatments is the\nexclusive source of all authoritative knowledge,\nthat there is valid knowledge (truth) only in scientific knowledge. Verified data received from the senses is known as\nempirical evidence. John J. Macionis, Linda M.\nGerber, \"Sociology\", Seventh Canadian Edition, Pearson Canada This view,\nwhen applied to the social as to the natural sciences, holds that society\noperates according to general laws like the physical world. Introspective and\nintuitive knowledge is rejected.\n\nThough the positivist approach has been a recurrent theme in the history of\nWestern thought, . modern sense of the\napproach was developed by the philosopher and founding sociologist Auguste Comte\nin the early 19th century. Comte argued that, much as the physical\nworld operates according to gravity and other absolute laws, so also does\nsociety.\n","linknr":1384,"url":"Positivism","recorded":1362373678,"links":89,"instances":["statistics","sociology","fallacy","philosophy","personal_and_cultural","geographer","literature","bureaucratic","sociology","mathematician","philosopher","sociology","british_political_party","philosophy","philosophy"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Philosophy of science","Philosophy of social science","Political philosophy","Epistemological theories","20th-century philosophy","19th-century philosophy","History of philosophy","Philosophy of law","Sociological paradigms","Sociological theories","Positivism|","Sociology index"],"headings":["Etymology","Overview","Sociological positivism","Logical positivism","Further thinkers","Positivism in science today","Criticisms","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/8/82/Plato%2C_Confucius%2C_Avicenna.png/180px-Plato%2C_Confucius%2C_Avicenna.png"